  "prompt": "How is the ionization energy of hydrogen atom determined?",
  "response": "The ionization energy of a hydrogen atom is the energy required to remove the electron from the ground state (the lowest energy state, which is also referred to as the 1s state) of the atom, converting it into a free proton and a free electron. This process can be described by the following equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{H} \\rightarrow \\text{H}^+ + e^- \\]\n\nTo determine the ionization energy of hydrogen, we typically use the principles of quantum mechanics and the energy levels of the hydrogen atom, which can be described by the Bohr model or more advanced quantum mechanical models.\n\n### Bohr Model Approach:\n\n1. **Energy Levels**: According to the Bohr model, the energy levels \\( E_n \\) of a hydrogen atom are given by the formula:\n\n   \\[\n   E_n = -\\frac{13.6 \\, \\text{eV}}{n^2}\n   \\]\n\n   where \\( n \\) is the principal quantum number (1, 2, 3,...). For the ground state of hydrogen, \\( n = 1 \\).\n\n2. **Ground State Energy**: The energy of the hydrogen atom in the ground state (n=1) is:\n\n   \\[\n   E_1 = -\\frac{13.6 \\, \\text{eV}}{1^2} = -13.6 \\, \\text{eV}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Ionization Energy Calculation**: The ionization energy is the energy needed to move the electron from this ground state to a point where it is no longer bound to the nucleus (where the energy is 0 eV). Therefore, the ionization energy \\( I \\) can be calculated as the difference in energy between the ground state and the point of ionization:\n\n   \\[\n   I = 0 \\, \\text{eV} - E_1 = 0 \\, \\text{eV} - (-13.6 \\, \\text{eV}) = 13.6 \\, \\text{eV}\n   \\]\n\n### Quantum Mechanical Approach:\n\nIn a more sophisticated quantum mechanical treatment (using Schr\u00f6dinger's equation), one would derive the same result for the ionization energy. The wave functions and the corresponding energy states of the hydrogen atom also yield the same ground state energy of -13.6 eV, confirming that the ionization energy is 13.6 eV.\n\n### Summary:\n\nThe ionization energy of the hydrogen atom is determined primarily by calculating the energy difference between the electron's energy in the ground state and at infinite separation from the nucleus (ionized state). The well-established value for the ionization energy of hydrogen is approximately **13.6 electron volts (eV)**.",
